on mountaintops 
where condors soar 
the people once believed 
in a terrible bargain 

exchanged for life-giving rain 
their children's innocent eyes 
closed forever 
in frozen grasp 

of Apu mountain gods 
who demanded more 
with each passing season 
a fresh crop of tiny hearts 

beaten with fear 
by those who should protect 
the soft whispers of "mama" 
drowned out by screams 

in the name of fertility 
they gave up their most precious 
bundles of joy 
left to suffocate 
in the thin Andean air 

for the promise of wet skies 
and green fields awash 
with the blood of innocence 
pooled at their feet 

what cruel deity 
requires such a toll?

** warning: this poem contains graphic and disturbing content **

on mountaintops 
they left them 
small bodies frozen in time 
innocence exchanged for rain 

a price to pay 
for fertile land 
for crops that grew 
and rivers that flowed 

their cries 
echoed through valleys 
as they were led 
to the altar of appeasement 

the gods demanded blood 
in exchange for life 
and so they gave 
what was most precious 

little hearts beat no more 
their laughter silenced 
forever trapped 
in the ice of sacrifice 

in the name of progress 
in the name of fertility 
they took what was not theirs 
to take 

and when the rains came 
did they wash away 
the guilt of their deeds?

the land is parched 
and dry as bone 
they say it's a curse 
unless we make it rain 

in the name of fertility 
we offer our most precious 
tiny hands bound 
tiny feet trampled 

a sacrifice to the skies 
to ensure the harvest thrives 
the old ways whisper secrets 
of life-giving showers 

in the high places 
where the gods reside 
they wait for our offering 
our greatest fear inside 

the sound of weeping 
echoes through the hills 
as mothers surrender 
their most tender wills 

for the promise of green 
and life-giving streams 
we lay our children down 
in ancient, bloody dreams 

the priests chant their mantras 
as the sun dips low 
the people hold their breath 
will the rains finally come?

**the mountain's thirst**

on sacred peaks 
they left their young 
as offerings to the gods 

promises of fertility 
danced on lips 
whispers of rainfall sweet 

in times of drought 
their desperation grew 
like withered crops 

they chose the innocent 
to plead for mercy 
soft skin and curious eyes 

bound and carried up 
the windswept slopes 
tears fell like the first drops 

the cries of children 
echoed off stone 
as they were laid to rest 

prayers were uttered 
pleading for the skies 
to weep and bring new life 

but at what cost 
do we bargain fate?

their tiny bodies 
strewn across the mountainside 
like discarded petals 
of some ancient flower 

the incas believed 
their screams would summon 
the rains that would quench 
their parched lands 

they chose the pure ones 
the ones with the clearest eyes 
and skin like alabaster 
unblemished by the world's cruelty 

these little gods 
were offered up to the skies 
to appease the wrathful deities 
who withheld the life-giving waters 

their mothers wept 
in secret chambers deep 
where the echoes of their grief 
would not be heard by the priests 

who ordained this horror 
this abomination of faith 
that promised fertility 
but delivered only death 

their bones remain 
a testament to our shame 
a reminder of the horrors 
we've inflicted in the name 

of progress,2019 
of prosperity 
of rainfall that never came 

and still we wonder 
why the earth weeps tears of stone 
why the skies remain dry 
and unforgiving as bone

on mountaintops 
where gods once roamed 
the innocent were chosen 
to atone for drought 

small hands bound 
with rope and fate 
their cries echoed off the peaks 
as they awaited rain's decree 

elders whispered secrets 
of an ancient pact 
to pacify the skies 
they offered up their youth 

in canopied forests 
shadows danced with fear 
mothers wept in silence 
as their children disappeared 

the high priests 
with eyes that burned bright 
promised fertility 
in exchange for life 

yet when rains did come 
it brought no solace deep 
for those who mourned 
the price they'd had to keep 

in Andean valleys 
where myths still linger 
whispers of a dark past 
haunt like a lingering shiver 

the weight of tradition 
crushed their tender bones 
leaving only questions 
of a cruel, forgotten throne
